[3] Bean necrotic mosaic virus - Brazil: new _Tospovirus_
Date: June 2012
Source: PLoS (Public Library of Science) ONE [edited]
http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0038634


[Ref: AS de Oliveira et al: Characterization of Bean necrotic mosaic virus: A member of a novel evolutionary lineage within the genus _Tospovirus_. PLoS ONE (2012) 7, e38634; DOI: 10.1371/journal.pone.0038634]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Tospoviruses (genus _Tospovirus_, family _Bunyaviridae_) are responsible for significant worldwide crop losses. They have a tripartite negative and ambisense RNA genome. Transmission is by thrips in a circulative-propagative manner.

Biological (host range and symptomatology), serological, and molecular (sequencing and evolutionary studies) experiments were performed to characterize and differentiate Bean necrotic mosaic virus (BeNMV), which naturally infects common beans in Brazil. Based upon the results, BeNMV can be classified as a novel species and, together with Soybean vein necrosis-associated virus (SVNaV), represents a new evolutionary lineage within the genus _Tospovirus_.

The evidence suggests that 2 divergent lineages of tospoviruses are circulating in the American continent and, based on the main clades diversity (American and Eurasian lineages), new tospovirus species related to the BeNMV-SVNaV clade remain to be discovered.

Further studies may reveal greater tospovirus diversity not only in the Americas (where both viruses were reported), but also throughout the world, increasing the [potential] economic impact [of tospoviruses] on agriculture.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
