[4] Soybean vein necrosis virus - USA: update
Date: Fri 24 Aug 2012
Source: The Bulletin, University of Illinois [edited]
http://bulletin.ipm.illinois.edu/article.php?id=1707


A new virus to notice in soybeans
---------------------------------
If you've been monitoring soybean fields for late-season pests, you may have noticed large, brown, blotchy lesions that run in the direction of the leaf veins. That symptom is characteristic of a new disease of soybean called Soybean vein necrosis virus, or SVNV.

A 2010 survey of soybean fields conducted by Les Domier, University of Illinois, showed that the disease is found throughout Illinois and is the 2nd-most prevalent virus found in Illinois soybean fields, right after _Bean pod mottle virus_. That is an amazing feat for a pathogen that not only causes a new disease but also is itself a newly described virus.

The virus is transmitted to soybean by the insect thrips. Domier notes that SVNV is in the tospo family of viruses, unusual in that they replicate not only in an infected plant but also in their thrips vectors. So thrips that are carrying SVNV can transmit it for a long time.

Symptoms of SVNV in Illinois typically start showing up in August, which is certainly the case this year [2012]. Initial studies and observations in Arkansas note that symptoms do vary with the cultivar, as we seem to be seeing here. Let's hope that this points to a source of genetic resistance, as has been the case for other pathogens.

[Byline: Suzanne Bissonnette]

[Additional news stories:
http://extension.psu.edu/field-crop-news/news/2012/07/soybean-vein-necrosis-virus (Pennsylvania) and
http://agfax.com/2012/08/24/kentucky-soybeans-watch-for-new-virus-disease/ (Kentucky).]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Mastreviruses
-------------
Until now, the African streak virus group of the mastreviruses included _Maize streak virus_ (MSV; type species of genus _Mastrevirus_), _Sugarcane streak virus_ (SSV), _Sugarcane streak Reunion virus_ (SSRV) and _Panicum streak virus_ (PanSV). Mastreviruses are important pathogens of cereal crops and are transmitted by leafhopper vectors (family _Cicadellidae_). MSV and the new species described in item [1] above with the preliminary name of Maize streak Reunion virus (MSRV) are the only 2 mastreviruses reported in maize. A possible synergistic enhancement of disease in coinfections of the 2 maize viruses needs to be considered. Since MSRV is highly divergent from the other members of the group, it will be important to investigate its epidemiology and host range so that its threat to maize production can be assessed.

Citrus tristeza
---------------
_Citrus tristeza virus_ (CTV; genus _Closterovirus_) is considered to be one of the most destructive citrus viruses. Besides citrus species (family of _Rutacea_), it affects hosts in only few other families, and it appears to be spreading wherever citrus is grown. Different strains of CTV may vary in severity and may occur singly or in combination. Symptoms also depend on the citrus variety and the scion- rootstock combination. The virus is spread by several aphid species and can also be transmitted by grafting and mechanical means. Disease management for CTV includes clean planting stock and budwood, elimination of inoculum, and vector control. Introduction of more severe strains is a constant risk even in CTV-affected areas, and thus the identification of a new phylogenetic group in Oman in item [2] is an important finding.

Tospoviruses
------------
Tospoviruses (type member _Tomato spotted wilt virus_, TSWV) are an extremely important group of plant viruses capable of infecting a large range of crops. They are transmitted exclusively by thrips species which are found worldwide. Weed species can serve as pathogen or vector reservoirs and tospovirus epidemiology is complex. Disease management is difficult but may include vector control (for glasshouse crops), use of clean planting material, control of weed hosts of virus and vectors, phytosanitary measures, and use of resistant crop cultivars. Due to their agricultural importance, research on tospoviruses has increased dramatically in recent years. As a result, many new species are being found and many more can be expected to exist.

A previously unknown virus was first identified in Tennessee in 2008 and in Illinois and Kentucky in 2009 (see ProMED-mal post 20100922.3430) as the cause of a new disease of soybeans. Symptoms observed included vein clearing that becomes necrotic as leaves mature leading to large necrotic regions on leaves and reduced plant vigour. The name Soybean vein necrosis(-associated) virus (SVNV/SVNaV) was suggested and preliminary classification placed it in the genus _Tospovirus_. However, it had minimal similarity to previously characterised members of the genus and is now included in a new clade, together with the new Bean necrotic mosaic virus described in item [3]. SVNV was found to affect a range of soybean cultivars and may be widespread in parts of the US, but no information is available yet on its presence in other countries.

_Bean pod mottle virus_ (BPMV; genus _Comovirus_) mentioned in item [4] has been reported to cause more than 50 percent crop loss in soybeans in parts of the US (for more information on BPMV see link below).

